SIMPLE: discoid
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Discoid
<hw>Dis"coid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/
quoit-shaped, <?/ a round plate, quoit + <grk>e'i^dos</grk> form, shape:
cf. F. <ets>disco⟦ium⟧de</ets>. See <er>Disk</er>.]</ety> <def>Having
the form of a disk, as those univalve shells which have the whorls in
one plane, so as to form a disk, as the pearly nautilus.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Discoid flower</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a
compound flower, consisting of tubular florets only, as a tansy, lacking
the rays which are seen in the daisy and sunflower.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Discoid</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Discoid
<hw>Dis"coid</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Anything having the form of a
discus or disk; particularly, a discoid shell.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Discoidal</ent>⟦br⟧
